title: For Sale:  Remington 11-87 Police 12ga 7-shot 18"
postcontent:
Hate to sell it but to make a long story short, a happy wife makes for a happy life. Here are the details:

Condition: Used but good (LEO trade-in)
Make: Remington Arms
Model: 11-87 Police
Action: Semi-automatic
Gauge: 12
Capacity: 6 + 1
Barrel: 18"
Chamber: 2 3/4" or 3"
Finish: Parkerized
Stock/Forend: Black synthetic
Sights: Rifle sights
Extras: Vang Comp Systems dome safety, great 2-point tactical sling (make unknown), sling plate, brand new Limbsaver recoil pad, TacStar 6-round side saddle, 50 rds Federal XM127 2 3/4" 00 Buck (2 boxes)

Some cosmetic wear in a few spots:
- Magazine extension coupling looks like it was removed with pliers at one point because the finish is partially scratched off (not a big deal, you can reorder part #F99833 for $16.48 + shipping from Remington if it's important to you that it look new)
- Barrel clamp has a scuff on it from being taken on and off
- Couple minor scuffs on the barrel from handling/use
- Butt stock is informally "engraved" with "#5" (presumably from original LEO duty use)
- TacStar side saddle is missing 1 of 6 screws (not an issue...it is still rock solid with the other 5 screws)

Other than the cosmetic wear I just noted, this gun is in great condition internally. Both the gas system collars and the gas O-ring were replaced in the last couple years.

These 11-87s are built to last, reliable, accurate, and ready for action. I can't tell you the round count from the previous owner, but most LEO long guns don't get fired much, and the internal wear looks minimal. I've only fired 42 rds of 2 3/4" 00 Buck through it to test function. It performed flawlessly, and the rifle sights are dead on.

This shotgun retails for $900+ brand new with no extras. This gun is used, but it has a few nice extras and comes with 50 rds of quality ammo, so I think $700 is a fair price and I'm firm on it. You are welcome to test fire it before purchasing if you have a suitable place to do that. I can take you to an indoor range as long as you pick up your range fee. Email me for more pictures. Cash only, no trades.

All parts on the rifle were purchased new. The rifle is in burnt bronze, cerakoted parts include the Upper, Lower, and Handguard. Seekins Precision’s Integrated Rail Mounting technology (iRMT) uppers integrate the rail mounting points into the upper retaining the stiffness of a true monolithic upper while allowing the rails to be completely modular. This new upper design is considerably thicker in the most critical area and will aid in squeezing all of the potential accuracy out of your rifle. Instead of a standard barrel nut our iRMT system uses an externally threaded, Titanium barrel nut with 1-1/8” wrench flats on it for simple installation. No special proprietary wrenches needed.

The SP 223 Billet lower feature a unique design geared towards the serious tactical shooter. To ease assembly Seekins Precision eliminated the use of roll pins, hammers, punches and replaced them with custom screw in dowel pins. We installed an upper tensioning set screw, a set screw for trigger reset, relocated and retained the rear take down pin detent under the grip. Our ambidextrous bolt control allows the shooter to quickly drop the bolt or from either side of the firearm. postcontent: NAZI Proofed P-38 ser.#9996 Z. The origin of this gun is different.The Z series, both Mauser and Spreewerke (factories in Berlin) made the Z ser. The model mark CVQ is on this piece, meaning that it was made towards the end of the war. The V should have been a Y, but the stamp die broke making the Y look like a V. These guns were also known as " Last Ditch" P-38s. All #s match, including clip, and bakalite grips are in real good shape. I bought thie gun 31 years ago for $700 and that was a deal. It's a piece of Military history.

title: For Sale:  Post WW2 refurb Mosin PU sniper rifle dated 1943 with matching original scope
location: Apex, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
Here is my post ww2 mosin nagant PU sniper rifle. I've had this for about two years now and I was never a great shot with it. It has a near perfect bore, which is quite shiny, and improved action. The action was improved to help cycle rounds better, and for most ammo I've used, it's quite smooth. There are some rounds that it doesn't like, but I've mostly used silver tip Bulgarian surplus (I've cleaned the rifle thoroughly after shooting to prevent corrosion). There are a few parts of the stock that were messed up from shipping, but if you wish to refinish the stock it would be easy. The rifle is a 1943 Izhevsk with the scope serial number matching the secondary serial number on the side of the receiver. The scope is in fantastic shape despite being almost as old as the rifle. It is Soviet made scope from Omsk plant 325 "progress", it has refubish mark on it and I think the mount is a reproduction. This is one of the earlier rifles imported from the Molot factory into the USA. Overall, the rifle is in fantastic shape and needs somebody to appreciate it more than I do. I will throw in a soft case and 20 rounds of Bulgarian surplus ammo. I will send additional photos upon request.

I will trade for a yugo, converted saiga, or foreign made 7.62x39 ak.
